`afplay` doesn't work from this context because there's no audio device attached to this process. That's fine — the 200 response and 172KB output confirms it works.

Now, the user can use OpenRouter by putting this config:

```json
{
  "readback": {
    "provider": "openai",
    "baseUrl": "https://openrouter.ai/api/v1",
    "model": "openai/gpt-4o-mini-tts-2025-12-15"
  }
}
```

And using their existing `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` env var. The provider already checks `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` as a fallback.

Let me tell the user this.

content.text:
OpenRouter TTS works — 200 response, 172KB audio. Your `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` is valid for this.

Here's what you need in `~/.config/pi-speak/config.json`:

```json
{
  "readback": {
    "provider": "openai",
    "baseUrl": "https://openrouter.ai/api/v1",
    "model": "openai/gpt-4o-mini-tts-2025-12-15"
  }
}
```

The provider already checks `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` as fallback (tries `OPENAI_API_KEY` first, then `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`). No need for a separate OpenAI key — your existing OpenRouter key just works.

Only difference vs direct OpenAI: the model name needs the `openai/` prefix, and the base URL points to OpenRouter. Everything else (voice names, `instructions` parameter, speed, format) is the same.

{
  "readback": {
    "provider": "openai",
    "baseUrl": "https://openrouter.ai/api/v1",
    "model": "openai/gpt-4o-mini-tts-2025-12-15"
  }
}

